Specimen From Organism ID (Required): A unique ID for the biomaterial.
Donor Organism ID (Required): A unique ID for the biomaterial.
COLLECTION PROTOCOL ID (Required): A unique ID for the protocol.
SPECIMEN FROM ORGANISM NAME: A short, descriptive name for the biomaterial that need not be unique.
SPECIMEN FROM ORGANISM DESCRIPTION: A general description of the biomaterial.
SUPPLEMENTARY FILES: A list of filenames of biomaterial-level supplementary files.
INSDC SAMPLE ACCESSION: An International Nucleotide Sequence Database Collaboration (INSDC) sample accession.
HDBR ACCESSION: A Human Developmental Biology Resource (HDBR) sample accession.
GENUS SPECIES (Required): The scientific binomial name for the species of the specimen.
GENUS SPECIES ONTOLOGY ID: An ontology term identifier in the form prefix:accession.
GENUS SPECIES ONTOLOGY LABEL ONTOLOGY ID: The preferred label for the ontology term referred to in the ontology field. This may differ from the user-supplied value in the text field.
ORGAN (Required): A term that may be associated with an anatomy-related ontology term.
ORGAN ONTOLOGY ID: An ontology term identifier in the form prefix:accession.
ORGAN ONTOLOGY LABEL ONTOLOGY ID: The preferred label for the ontology term referred to in the ontology field. This may differ from the user-supplied value in the text field.
ORGAN PART: A term for a specific part of the organ that the biomaterial came from.
ORGAN PART ONTOLOGY ID: An ontology term identifier in the form prefix:accession.
ORGAN PART ONTOLOGY LABEL ONTOLOGY ID: The preferred label for the ontology term referred to in the ontology field. This may differ from the user-supplied value in the text field.
KNOWN DISEASE(S): Short description of known disease(s) of the specimen.
KNOWN DISEASE(S) ONTOLOGY ID: An ontology term identifier in the form prefix:accession.
KNOWN DISEASE(S) ONTOLOGY LABEL ONTOLOGY: The preferred label for the ontology term referred to in the ontology field. This may differ from the user-supplied value in the text field.
AUTOLYSIS SCORE: State of tissue breakdown due to self-digestion.
GROSS DESCRIPTION: Color, size, and other aspects of specimen as visible to naked eye.
GROSS IMAGE: List of filenames of photographs of specimen without magnification.
ISCHEMIC TEMPERATURE: Whether specimen experienced warm or cold ischemia.
ISCHEMIC TIME: Duration of time, in seconds, between when the specimen stopped receiving oxygen and when it was preserved or processed.
MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION: How the specimen looks under the microscope and how it compares with normal cells.
MICROSCOPIC IMAGE: List of filenames of photographs of specimen under microscope.
POST-MORTEM INTERVAL: Duration of time between when death was declared and when the specimen was preserved or processed.
STORAGE METHOD: The method by which a biomaterial was stored after preservation or before another protocol was used.
STORAGE TIME: Length of time the biomaterial was stored for in Storage time units.
STORAGE TIME UNIT: A term that may be associated with a time unit-related ontology term.
STORAGE TIME UNIT ONTOLOGY ID: An ontology term identifier in the form prefix:accession.
STORAGE TIME UNIT ONTOLOGY LABEL ONTOLOG: The preferred label for the ontology term referred to in the ontology field. This may differ from the user-supplied value in the text field.
PRESERVATION METHOD: The method by which a biomaterial was preserved through the use of chemicals, cold, or other means to prevent or retard biological or physical deterioration.

COLLECTION PROTOCOL ID (Required): Protocol ID should have no spaces.
GENOTYPE: For example: DRB1 0401 protective allele; HLA-B*3901 allele
BIOSAMPLES ACCESSION: Enter accession if sample has been archived. Accession can be from the DDBJ, NCBI, or EMBL-EBI and must start with SAMD, SAMN, or SAME, respectively. For example: SAMN00000000
INSDC SAMPLE ACCESSION: Enter accession if sample has been archived. Accession can be from the DDBJ, NCBI, or EMBL-EBI and must start with DRS, SRS, or ERS, respecitvely. For example: SRS0000000
HDBR ACCESSION: Enter accession if sample has been obtained from the Human Developmental Biology Resource (HDBR). For example: 34526; 14758, 2, liver
GENUS SPECIES (Required): For example: Homo sapiens; Mus musculus
GENUS SPECIES ONTOLOGY LABEL ONTOLOGY ID: For example: Homo sapiens; Mus musculus
ORGAN PART: The term organ part is very broadly defined here. For example: bone marrow; islet of Langerhans
ORGAN PART ONTOLOGY LABEL ONTOLOGY ID: For example: bone marrow; islet of Langerhans
KNOWN DISEASE(S): Enter normal if no known diseases. For example: type 2 diabetes mellitus; normal
KNOWN DISEASE(S) ONTOLOGY LABEL ONTOLOGY: For example: type 2 diabetes mellitus; normal
AUTOLYSIS SCORE: For example: Should be one of: none, mild, or moderate.
GROSS DESCRIPTION: For example: focal wedge shaped region of tan-orange discoloration; cystic
GROSS IMAGE: File must be of format JPEG, TIFF, or PNG. For example: my_gross_image_file.jpg
ISCHEMIC TEMPERATURE: For example: Should be one of: warm, or cold.
MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION: For example: Mixture of different cell sizes apparent; Dead cells are quite faint on microscope
MICROSCOPIC IMAGE: File must be of format JPEG, TIFF, or PNG. For example: my_microscopic_image_file.jpg
POST-MORTEM INTERVAL: Enter time in seconds. For example: 2400
STORAGE METHOD: For example: frozen in liquid nitrogen; fresh
PRESERVATION METHOD: Enter 'fresh' if not preserved. For example: cryopreservation in liquid nitrogen (dead tissue); fresh
TIME OF COLLECTION: Enter the time in date-time format: yyyy-mm-ddThh:mm:ssZ. Supplying partial date is allowed. For example: 2016-01-21T00:00:00Z; 2016-03
